    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-11-20T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-11-20T07:00:00-05:00" n="720"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d720">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">761.94/1241: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-11-20T15:00:00+03:00"
                            >November 20, 1940—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 5:30 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1584. My 1577, November 19, 1 p.m.<note n="95" xml:id="d720fn95">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_584">p. 584</ref>.</note>
                    Further intimations from the same source<note n="96" xml:id="d720fn96">A member
                        of the German Embassy in the Soviet Union who “accompanied the German
                        Ambassador to Berlin with Molotov.”</note> referred to in my telegram under
                    reference would indicate that at least one of the conditions which the Soviet
                    Union is demanding for the conclusion of an agreement with Japan is the entire
                    abandonment of the Japanese coal and oil concessions on the northern part of
                    Sakhalin.</p>
                <p>I have learned from another diplomatic source that the Soviet conditions have
                    been conveyed directly or indirectly to the Japanese Ambassador here. The
                    Japanese, however, according to my informant, are at the present time not
                    disposed to relinquish their concessions on the northern part of Sakhalin which
                    would be in conformity with the statements of the Japanese Ambassador to me
                    reported in my No. 1466, November 1, 6 p.m., in regard to the importance to
                    Japan of these concessions.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
